          "title": "The city inventory — the density of the gift (15:20-62)",
          "body": "Over one hundred cities are cataloged across four districts: the southern Negev, the Shephelah (coastal foothills), the hill country, and the wilderness margins. Modern readers who skip these lists should at minimum observe their structural function: they make the inheritance specific. The land the LORD gives to Judah is not an abstraction or a spiritual metaphor; it is Lachish and Azekah (where Joshua defeated Canaanite kings, Joshua 10:31-35), Hebron (where the patriarchs are buried, Genesis 23), En-gedi (the oasis on the Dead Sea shore where David will later hide from Saul, 1 Samuel 24:1), and Beersheba (where Abraham made a covenant with Abimelech, Genesis 21:31). Every city on the list has a story; the inventory is dense with covenant memory. The four districts also reflect the ecological comprehensiveness of the grant — arid desert, agricultural foothills, forested highland, and barren wilderness margins all belong to Judah. The LORD gives the whole landscape, not just the productive terrain. Calvin observed that the detailed recording of Israel's inheritance in Canaan was meant to strengthen faith: when the people read the list, they were to see God's faithfulness rendered in concrete names, not in general principles."
