        "title": "The city inventory — naming the gift in full",
        "range": "15:20-62",
        "excerpt": "This is the inheritance of the tribe of the sons of Judah according to their families.",
        "body": "The summary formula of verse 20 — 'this is the inheritance of the tribe of the sons of Judah according to their families' — introduces a city catalog that modern readers routinely skip and ancient readers would have read as a legal title deed. Over one hundred named cities are enumerated across four geographic districts: the Negev south (vv. 21-32, 29 cities), the Shephelah lowland (vv. 33-47, subdivided into multiple groups), the hill country (vv. 48-60, grouped into sub-districts), and the wilderness margins (vv. 61-62, 6 cities). The systematic organization by terrain is not bureaucratic — it is the narrator's way of showing that the LORD's gift encompasses the full ecological diversity of Judah's territory.\n\nThe names that appear in this list are not blank place-names to a biblically literate reader. Lachish (v. 39) is the city Joshua destroyed in the great southern coalition battle (Joshua 10:31-32); its appearance in the city list confirms it belongs to Judah after conquest. Azekah (v. 35) is the city before which Joshua called the sun to stand still (Joshua 10:10-12). Makkedah (v. 41) is where five Amorite kings hid in a cave and were executed (Joshua 10:16-28). Hebron (v. 54, appearing in the hill-country list as Kiriath-arba) is the patriarchal burial ground and the city Caleb just conquered (v. 13). En-gedi (v. 62) will be the oasis wilderness where David hides from Saul (1 Samuel 24:1). Ziklag (v. 31) will be the city Achish of Gath gives to David during his Philistine exile (1 Samuel 27:6). Beersheba (v. 28) is where Abraham planted a tamarisk tree and called on the name of the LORD (Genesis 21:33). The inventory is saturated with covenant memory. John Calvin, in his Lectures on Joshua, argued that the detailed enumeration of cities and boundaries was provided precisely so that later generations would recognize the faithfulness of God — when David rules from Hebron, when Solomon builds in Jerusalem, when the exiles return to named towns, the original grant can be checked against the reality.\n\nThe inclusion of Philistine cities in the southwestern inventory — Ekron, Ashdod, and Gaza (vv. 45-47) — is particularly striking. These cities are inside Judah's allotted territory but are explicitly Philistine strongholds. The narrator lists them as belonging to Judah without noting their failure to be conquered — that failure will emerge gradually in Judges and Samuel. The Philistines will not be a settled problem until David's campaigns (2 Samuel 8:1), and Gaza will remain contested even further into biblical history. The inclusion of these cities in the allotment anticipates the Davidic conquest before it happens: the title is given before the possession is complete.\n\nCalvin's observation about the city lists applies with full force here: the enumeration is not tedious — it is the legal record of what God promised and gave. When Israel later loses territory to foreign powers, the lists of Joshua stand as the legal baseline of divine grant. They function like a title deed to which Israel can return and say: the LORD gave us this. The gift does not expire because possession has lapsed.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Nachalah* (inheritance, v.20) — the covenant term for one's divinely assigned portion; related to *nachal* (stream) by root, suggesting the inheritance 'flows' to its recipient by covenant right. *Chatser* (villages) — the dependent settlements clustered around a main city; every group-summary includes 'their villages,' indicating the grant covers not just walled cities but the entire agricultural hinterland."
